CMNE
========================
## Enumeration
You can tell a site is running WordPress if the source code references `wp-content` or `plugins` or `themes`. It's not that hard to ID WordPress. 
```bash
wpscan --enumerate --url <URL>
```

## Basic Attacks
Without exploiting certain plugins or themes there is a lot you can do against wordpress. 

### Login Bruteforce
Two ways to BF a WP Login, using `wp-login` and using `xmlrpc`. `xmlrpc` is faster. 

```bash
sudo wpscan --password-attack xmlrpc -t 20 -U <user> -P <passlist> --url <URL>
```
`-U` can also be a list of users. 

### Authorized RCE
This is a basic technique for any CMS, really. Just adjust the code of an uncommon page to contain a webshell, or add your own. I like [this webshell](https://github.com/WhiteWinterWolf/wwwolf-php-webshell). But you can also just inject the classic one-liner. 

_Remember_: Most of the vulnerabilities that occur in WordPresss come from the Plugins (~90%), so always check them for initial access. 